Rating: 3
The onions take way longer to carmelize than the recipe says - probably about double the time. When it came time to put the mushrooms in, we half-heartedly deglazed the pot with a few tablespoons of the white wine, reserving the liquid with the onions. There was a lot of onion stuck to the pot, and I was concerned that once the mushrooms were sauteed, that it would burn and spoil the flavor. We used homemade vegetable stock instead of store-bought and opted for brandy. It's a good soup -- an interesting take on French onion -- though I'd say not so different taste-wise in the final analysis. The portobellos really give it more texture than they do discernable flavor. The goat cheese, however, made for an interesting difference from the usual swiss cheese, and accentuated what mushroom flavor there was. I'd make this again, but with 3/4 lb. of mushrooms (maybe criminis, because I think they lend better to broths than portobellos, which don't give up as much of their flavor when sauteed), and 2 lbs. of onions. It was definitely a good soup, though, rich in flavor with a wonderful aroma.

